   =20
      SVB poaching
   =20
 =20

Loosely speaking,=C2=A0Silicon Valley Bank consisted of:
=09Some bank deposits;=09Some long-term US government bonds that lost a lot=
 of value as interest rates went up; and=09Strong customer relationships wi=
th top tech startups and venture capital firms.

If you acquired all of SVB =E2=80=94=C2=A0for instance by buying it from th=
e US Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. after it failed and was seized =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0then you would get all of those things. The liabilities (Thing 1) =
seem to have been bigger than the assets (Thing 2), making the net value of=
 SVB=E2=80=99s balance sheet=C2=A0negative. Which is awkward: You=C2=A0coul=
d=C2=A0pay the FDIC a negative amount of money for SVB, and in fact the buy=
er =E2=80=94=C2=A0First Citizens Bank & Trust Co. =E2=80=94=C2=A0did pay a =
negative amount of money=C2=A0(for much but not all of SVB), but the FDIC w=
as not really looking for a negative amount of money and it renders the neg=
otiations unpleasant.
In general, Thing 3 has a positive but uncertain value. If some other bank =
had bought SVB in, like, January, it might have paid a positive amount of m=
oney for the whole bank: Sure the assets were worth less than the liabiliti=
es, but the=C2=A0business=C2=A0was valuable, not just the balance sheet. If=
 you acquire a beloved bank with strong customer relationships, you can mak=
e money on that, even if its current pile of assets happens to be worth les=
s than what it owes depositors.
But=C2=A0once you are negotiating with the FDIC to buy SVB out of receivers=
hip you might worry that those customer relationships have decayed a bit.
Also you can just buy them directly, for cheap, without messing around with=
 the balance sheet? Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Joel Rosenblatt reports:

First Citizens Bank & Trust Co. sued HSBC Holdings Plc for allegedly raidin=
g dozens of employees from Silicon Valley Bank in a scheme dubbed =E2=80=9C=
Project Colony=E2=80=9D as First Citizens was taking over the failed Califo=
rnia lender.=C2=A0
Two weeks after First Citizens acquired SVB on March 27, HSBC poached 42 ba=
nkers on Easter Sunday and brazenly took and misused SVB=E2=80=99s confiden=
tial, proprietary and trade secret information, according to a complaint fi=
led Monday in federal court in northern California.
David Sabow, who worked in a health-care and technology banking practice at=
 SVB before jumping to HSBC, is identified in the complaint as =E2=80=9Cthe=
 chief architect of this scheme,=E2=80=9D which aimed to plunder what was t=
hought to be the =E2=80=9Ccore of SVB=E2=80=99s profitability engine,=E2=80=
=9D according to the complaint. Sabow helped to identify six core US leader=
s to hire, along with 35 additional SVB professionals, according to the com=
plaint.

Yes right if there=E2=80=99s an insolvent bank you want to acquire its=C2=
=A0profitability engine=C2=A0and leave its=C2=A0balance sheet=C2=A0behind.

 =20
   =20
      Patent sub-trolls
   =20
 =20

If you invent a thing and patent it, and then somebody else makes a similar=
 thing that infringes on your patent, you can sue them. For various reasons=
, this may be inconvenient for you, as an inventor: You may not have money =
to pay for lawyers, or you might be too busy inventing and making stuff to =
sue, etc.
But you can sell your patents to somebody else. You can, for instance, sell=
 your patent to somebody who is not in the business of inventing and making=
 things, but who is in the business of acquiring patents and=C2=A0suing peo=
ple who make things that allegedly infringe on the patents. This is a busin=
ess that benefits from scale; the people in this business =E2=80=94=C2=A0so=
metimes called =E2=80=9Cnon-practicing entities,=E2=80=9D or more=C2=A0pejo=
ratively =E2=80=9Cpatent trolls=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0will want to acquir=
e lots of patents and sue a lot to maximize their returns.
The downside of scale in litigation is that, if you are constantly suing ev=
eryone in the world for infringing on your portfolio of patents, people are=
 going to start rolling their eyes when they see your lawsuits. =E2=80=9CTh=
ese guys again,=E2=80=9D they will say. =E2=80=9CPatent trolls,=E2=80=9D th=
ey will say.
But you can sell your patents to somebody else. You can, for instance, find=
 some guy, and give him one of your patents, and then pay for him to sue pe=
ople who make things that allegedly infringe on the patents, and sign an ag=
reement with him where he=E2=80=99ll give you most of the money if he wins =
and just keep a little tip for himself for letting you use his name. And th=
en when=C2=A0he=C2=A0sues,=C2=A0he=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=99t have a long history=
 of patent litigation, and maybe people won=E2=80=99t roll their eyes at hi=
m.
Or maybe they will. The Wall Street Journal reports:

A federal judge in Delaware is on a campaign to eliminate hidden funding of=
 intellectual-property lawsuits against companies, a crackdown that is roil=
ing the patent-law industry.
U.S. Chief District Judge Colm Connolly in Wilmington, whose court is one o=
f the busiest venues for patent litigation, issued an order a year ago requ=
iring litigants in his court to disclose details of any financial arrangeme=
nts in which third parties are funding their lawsuits.=C2=A0
Lawyers defending companies against infringement claims have cheered him on=
, crediting the judge with exposing tactics that have shielded filers of fr=
ivolous lawsuits from scrutiny and liability. Attorneys representing plaint=
iffs in the judge=E2=80=99s crosshairs have accused Connolly of unjustly pr=
ying into their clients=E2=80=99 finances and privileged communications. =
=E2=80=A6
The largest fallout from Connolly=E2=80=99s campaign involves IP Edge, a Ho=
uston-based company that makes money acquiring vast bundles of patents and =
litigating them in court. ...
Last summer he summoned several Texas residents identified as sole owners o=
f plaintiff companies to testify at evidentiary hearings he convened in Nov=
ember.
The witnesses, a paralegal from Fort Worth, a software salesman from Housto=
n and a food-truck owner from Waco, testified that they came to own the rig=
hts to patents through a consulting firm called Mavexar that approached the=
m.
Public records show that Mavexar=E2=80=99s three principal members are the =
same patent attorneys that founded IP Edge. A lawyer for IP Edge declined t=
o comment.
The witnesses all testified that Mavexar created limited liability companie=
s=E2=80=94naming them as managing members=E2=80=94and transferred patent ri=
ghts to the companies. Mavexar retained attorneys for the LLCs, handled com=
munications with the lawyers and controlled decisions about wielding the pa=
tents in litigation, they said. The witnesses said they didn=E2=80=99t pay =
anything for the rights to the patents but Mavexar was entitled to 90%-95% =
of any litigation and settlement proceeds.=C2=A0

Why does no one ever approach=C2=A0me=C2=A0out of the blue to give=C2=A0me =
10% of some patent litigation? I mean, to be fair, I wouldn=E2=80=99t belie=
ve them, and I=E2=80=99d probably write about it. Still.=C2=A0

 =20
   =20
      Bitcoin conference
   =20
 =20

Every year (every week?), there is a big Bitcoin conference in Miami, for s=
ome value of =E2=80=9Cevery,=E2=80=9D and of =E2=80=9Cbig.=E2=80=9D Obvious=
ly there was not a big Bitcoin conference in Miami in, like, 2006. Will the=
re be a big Bitcoin conference in 2026? Probably? I don=E2=80=99t know. Now=
 we are=C2=A0in a crypto winter, and 2023=E2=80=99s Bitcoin conferences are=
 not as big or as cheerful as they were in 2021 or 2022, but they are still=
 happening, and they are still very very Bitcoin-y. The Wall Street Journal=
  went to this year=E2=80=99s (this week=E2=80=99s?) conference and, while =
=E2=80=9Corganizers expected only half as many people to attend compared wi=
th last year,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s still full of stuff like this:

On Thursday, the first day of the conference that is reserved for high-acce=
ss ticket holders, people broke conversations when pallbearers and Black go=
spel choristers approached, belting out =E2=80=9CWhen the Saints Go Marchin=
g In.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The pallbearers struggled to lift an open casket over security scanners as =
they made their way into the convention center. Inside was a slew of dollar=
 bills and a label reading =E2=80=9C#FiatFuneral.=E2=80=9D One chorister ca=
rried a sign reading =E2=80=9CHallelujah Bitcoin.=E2=80=9D

I mean, sure.
Last year, crypto custody firm BitGo held a party where it served two sushi=
-grade tuna that chefs cut and carved up for guests, one of which clocked i=
n at 200 pounds. This year, there was just one tuna, a 115-pounder, though =
the company made a joke of it, handing out stickers reading =E2=80=9C#TunaW=
inter.=E2=80=9D
Not so bad, right? Last year there were two big tunas; this year there is o=
ne, somewhat smaller tuna: a retrenchment, sure, but not total capitulation=
. Still a party.=C2=A0Also here is an amazing fact:
A satellite event called Sh*tcoin Conference, which celebrates non-bitcoin =
cryptocurrencies viewed as worthless by some bitcoin believers, ended up sm=
aller after crypto exchange FTX imploded late last year. FTX was supposed t=
o sponsor it before its bankruptcy, forcing the organizers to scale the sch=
edule back considerably. Last year, the event was a two-day conference at t=
he nightclub Mad Club Wynwood. This year, it was one evening at a co-workin=
g space in Wynwood called the LAB Miami.=C2=A0
FTX was going to sponsor the Sh*tcoin Conference! =E2=80=9CWhich celebrates=
 non-bitcoin cryptocurrencies viewed as worthless by some bitcoin believers=
=E2=80=9D! Also by some other people! One quick story of the collapse of FT=
X would be that it took all of its customers=E2=80=99 money and traded it f=
or a pile of magic beans =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9CSamcoins=E2=80=9D =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0of its own invention, which turned out to be worthless. And=C2=A0a=
s it was doing that=C2=A0it was=C2=A0smirkingly agreeing to sponsor this co=
nference? Everything in crypto is so on-the-nose.

