   =20
      Paper money stuff
   =20
 =20

On the one hand, bank deposits compete with money market funds and Treasury=
 bills. If Treasury bills or money market funds pay 5% interest, and your b=
ank account pays 0.01%, you might move your money out of the bank. For bank=
s, this is bad, for reasons we have talked about extensively in recent mont=
hs: Basically the business model of banking relies on=C2=A0paying low inter=
est on deposits even as interest rates rise elsewhere, and if everyone star=
ts taking their money out of banks to put it into Treasuries then the banks=
 have problems.
On the other hand, bank deposits compete with a pile of $20 bills under you=
r mattress. For most people in the US, most of the time, bank accounts =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0which offer direct deposit, automatic bill payments, probably h=
igher security than your mattress, and maybe even interest =E2=80=94=C2=A0a=
re more attractive than bills under the mattress. But bills under the mattr=
ess have some advantages. There are=C2=A0some=C2=A0contexts where you can s=
pend them more easily than bank money; some businesses only take cash and a=
re not right next to an ATM. Plus if you are worried about your bank=E2=80=
=99s credit risk you might prefer the bills.
There are various dials of monetary policy and bank regulation that can be =
turned to make bank accounts more or less attractive. But there are also so=
me dials of paper-money regulation that governments can turn, and that=E2=
=80=99s=C2=A0one way to do=C2=A0financial stability regulation. Bloomberg=
=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Preeti Singh and Saikat Das report on the experience in Ind=
ia:

A key metric of profitability for Indian banks, lending margins, is set to =
get a boost as the nation=E2=80=99s decision to withdraw its highest-value =
currency note bolsters bank deposits.
The Reserve Bank of India=E2=80=99s move to withdraw the 2,000 rupees ($24)=
 notes will lead to growth in deposits at banks and lower their cost of fun=
ds, according to a note from Axis Mutual Fund. The step could boost deposit=
s by as much as 2 trillion rupees through the end-September deadline to exc=
hange the notes, the asset manager said. =E2=80=A6
As the rush to deposit the high-value currency notes before the deadline ga=
thers pace, banks=E2=80=99 margins could expand, said Madan Sabnavis, chief=
 economist at state-run Bank of Baroda.

If the biggest banknote denomination=C2=A0is no longer legal tender, then t=
he pile of bills under your mattress has to have more smaller-denomination=
=C2=A0bills, which makes the pile=C2=A0bigger, which makes your bed less co=
mfortable, which makes the pile of bills under your mattress a less attract=
ive competitor to bank=C2=A0deposits, which helps banks=E2=80=99 net intere=
st margins.
Elsewhere in paper money, here=E2=80=99s a guy:

Steven Ferry carries in his wallet=E2=80=94in addition to cash=E2=80=94a su=
pply of small cards created by one of a growing number of pro-cash groups t=
hat tout the benefits of physical money. He hands them to cashiers and leav=
es them on checks at restaurants.
=E2=80=9CI paid cash today for a reason :-)=E2=80=9D the cards read in part=
. =E2=80=9CUsing cash can be inconvenient=E2=80=A6but what if it=E2=80=99s =
worth it?=E2=80=9D

Just based on that description I bet you can make a pretty accurate sketch =
of his mustache.

