<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For many, many, many purposes in financial mar=
kets, you have to post collateral. Most importantly, if you want to borrow =
money in some of the=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/31573672.259422/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubmV3eW9ya2ZlZC5vcmcvZGF0YS1hbmQtc3R=
hdGlzdGljcy9kYXRhLXZpc3VhbGl6YXRpb24vdHJpLXBhcnR5LXJlcG8jaW50ZXJhY3RpdmUvdm=
9sdW1lL2NvbGxhdGVyYWxfdmFsdWU/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3c797f9a" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
biggest</a>=C2=A0lending markets,=C2=A0you put up some collateral and get t=
he money; when you repay the money you get the collateral back. If you do c=
ertain derivatives trades, you have to post collateral to ensure that you a=
re good for your obligations. If you want to sell a stock short, you borrow=
 the stock and post collateral to secure your obligation to return it. If y=
ou are a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31573672.=
259422/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDEt=
MjkvcmVkZGl0LXRyYWRlcnMtb24tcm9iaW5ob29kLWFyZS1vbi1ib3RoLXNpZGVzLW9mLWdhbWV=
zdG9wP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MjMyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdX=
JjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDUyMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3284c96d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  retail brokerage</a>, your custo=
mers do trades today but actually hand over the money on Friday, and meanwh=
ile you post collateral with a clearinghouse to guarantee their trades. The=
 plumbing of global finance works through collateral: You and I can agree t=
o do stuff in the future, without necessarily knowing each other well or tr=
usting each other much, because we have posted collateral to ensure that we=
=E2=80=99re good for our promises.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Often the way this=C2=A0works is that the coll=
ateral consists of some securities that you own,<a class=3D"footnote-index"=
 href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display:=
 inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> and the safer the securities are =E2=80=94=C2=A0the more likely they a=
re to retain their value =E2=80=94=C2=A0the better they are as collateral. =
The=C2=A0<em>best=C2=A0</em>collateral, for most things in US finance, is s=
hort-term US Treasury bills, which have no credit risk and very little inte=
rest-rate risk and=C2=A0are pretty much always worth a pretty predictable a=
mount. Longer-term Treasury bonds are also good, though they have more rate=
 risk.=C2=A0Some other kinds of collateral =E2=80=94 agency bonds, municipa=
l bonds, highly rated corporate and structured-finance bonds, etc. =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0are also quite good and acceptable for <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31573672.259422/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubmV3eW9ya2ZlZ=
C5vcmcvZGF0YS1hbmQtc3RhdGlzdGljcy9kYXRhLXZpc3VhbGl6YXRpb24vdHJpLXBhcnR5LXJl=
cG8jaW50ZXJhY3RpdmUvdm9sdW1lL2NvbGxhdGVyYWxfdmFsdWU/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cC3c797f9a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;"> many purposes</a>, though not all; some sorts of <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31573672.259422/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cubmV3eW9ya2ZlZC5vcmcvbWFya2V0cy9yZWZlcmVuY2UtcmF0ZXMvYWRkaXRpb25hbC=
1pbmZvcm1hdGlvbi1hYm91dC1yZWZlcmVuY2UtcmF0ZXMjdGdjcl9iZ2NyX3NvZnJfY2FsY3VsY=
XRpb25fbWV0aG9kb2xvZ3k/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9d159517" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">collatera=
l-demanding businesses</a> are very picky and will accept only Treasuries. =
And then there is a lot of other stuff: Junk bonds, penny stocks, private-c=
ompany stocks, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/315=
73672.259422/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMj=
MtMDUtMjIvYmFua3MtZ290LXJpc2luZy1yYXRlcy13cm9uZz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTIzMjNfTU9OR=
VlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0y=
MzA1MjMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb2ee955b" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;">  fractional ownership of racehorses</a>, any sort of financial ass=
et you can name. So much crypto. All of this stuff=C2=A0<em>could=C2=A0</em=
>be collateral, for some purposes; somebody would probably lend you money a=
gainst any of it. But if you bring it to the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/31573672.259422/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZHRjYy5jb20vY2xl=
YXJpbmctc2VydmljZXMvZmljYy1nb3YvZ2NmLXJlcG8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0f0813=
74" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> GCF repo market</a>=C2=A0or <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/31573672.259422/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnJiZGlzY291bnR3aW5=
kb3cub3JnL1BhZ2VzL0NvbGxhdGVyYWwvY29sbGF0ZXJhbF9lbGlnaWJpbGl0eQ/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cB0f7f3820" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the Fed=E2=80=99s discount window</a> they=
 will turn up their noses; they don=E2=80=99t take fractional racehorses th=
ere.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The point of the collateral, in a lot of the b=
ig=C2=A0markets, is to make things=C2=A0<em>easy=C2=A0</em>and <em>efficien=
t,=C2=A0</em>so nobody has to <em>think=C2=A0</em>about risk. <em>Somebody=
=C2=A0</em>will lend you money against a fractional racehorse or your start=
up shares, but they will think about it for a while and make a particular u=
nderwriting decision; they will be in the specialized business of lending m=
oney against weird assets. Financial-markets plumbing is different; it is a=
 big organized system that uses fungible collateral that everybody agrees i=
s good and that nobody has to think about specifically. Huge piles of simil=
ar, safe assets =E2=80=94=C2=A0like the trillions of dollars of reliable an=
d well-understood US Treasuries =E2=80=94=C2=A0work best; weird bespoke stu=
ff doesn=E2=80=99t work at all.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And of course if you have some bonds that are=
=C2=A0<em>in default</em>, where the issuer is not current on its interest =
and principal payments, they would be quite=C2=A0<em>bad=C2=A0</em>collater=
al. Not that they=E2=80=99re worthless, necessarily =E2=80=94=C2=A0maybe th=
e issuer will get its act together and start paying again =E2=80=94 just th=
at evaluating defaulted debt is a very specific skill. Many systems that de=
mand collateral would not even consider=C2=A0<em>defaulted bonds=C2=A0</em>=
as collateral; defaulted bonds are not at all the sort of safe, fungible as=
sets that work as collateral in deep and liquid markets</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so of course the question is, if Treasury =
bills are also defaulted bonds, what happens? Does everything break?=C2=A0<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31573672.259422/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMjIvdXMtZGVmYXVsd=
C1zY2VuYXJpb3Mtc3Bhbi1mcm9tLWxvY2FsaXplZC1wYWluLXRvLWRpbW9uLXMtcGFuaWM_Y21w=
aWQ9QkJEMDUyMzIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3N=
sZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNTIzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cB1f1631ac" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">  Chris Anstey and Liz McCormick report</a>:<=
/p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Investment bank clients are peppering Wall Str=
eet with questions about what happens if the US Treasury in coming weeks ru=
ns out of cash and does the unthinkable =E2=80=94 failing to make payments =
due on Treasury securities, the bedrock of the global financial system. =E2=
=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One school of thought is that the impact might=
 not be so damaging. After all, since the 2011 debt-limit crisis, market pa=
rticipants have worked out a process for dealing with the Treasury announci=
ng that it couldn=E2=80=99t make an interest or principal payment.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co. Chief Executive O=
fficer Jamie Dimon warned earlier this month that even going to the brink i=
s dangerous, with unpredictable consequences.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe closer you get to it, you will ha=
ve panic,=E2=80=9D he said in a May 11 interview with Bloomberg Television.=
 =E2=80=9CThe other thing about markets is that, always remember, panic is =
the one thing that scares people =E2=80=94 they take irrational decisions.=
=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And even a key group that helped to compile th=
e emergency procedures, the Federal Reserve Bank of New York-sponsored Trea=
sury Market Practices Group, has issued its own caution.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWhile the practices contemplated in t=
his document might, at the margin, reduce some of the negative consequences=
 of an untimely payment on Treasury debt for Treasury market functioning, t=
he TMPG believes the consequences of delaying payments would nonetheless be=
 severe,=E2=80=9D it said in its December 2021 gameplan.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWe are likely to see localized disloc=
ations in the event of missed payment,=E2=80=9D if that were to happen, JPM=
organ rates strategists, co-led by Jay Barry, wrote Friday in a Q&amp;A for=
 clients on a technical default.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">RBC Capital Markets strategists, also writing =
Friday, said they =E2=80=9Cdoubt=E2=80=9D a downgrade would trigger any for=
ced reallocation by fund managers away from Treasuries.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At the same time, RBC=E2=80=99s Blake Gwinn an=
d Izaac Brook cautioned that the =E2=80=9Cback-office issues=E2=80=9D of de=
laying payments =E2=80=9Ccould very easily bleed into the front-office, cau=
sing disruptions to liquidity and market functioning.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The TMPG noted that firms holding Treasuries i=
n custody for other financial institutions tend to advance payments schedul=
ed for those securities, and would need to sort how to proceed if those pay=
ments weren=E2=80=99t received from the Treasury on time.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Firms that offer pricing on Treasuries could r=
un into challenges, =E2=80=9Csuch as setting the price of a Treasury subjec=
t to a delayed payment to $0,=E2=80=9D the group said.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Some market participants =E2=80=9Cmight not be=
 able to implement=E2=80=9D the contingency plans, =E2=80=9Cand others coul=
d do so only with substantial manual intervention in their trading and sett=
lement processes, which itself would pose significant operational risk,=E2=
=80=9D the TMPG said.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yesterday <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/31573672.259422/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvZT=
Q2MzlmNzEtYjY5Zi00ZDk5LTg2N2QtZGZmZDE3MzM3NzlkP3NoYXJlVHlwZT1ub25naWZ0/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc312132e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> FT Alphaville published</a> much of=
 that JPMorgan rates strategy Q&amp;A, which I would say=C2=A0is broadly sa=
nguine about market=C2=A0plumbing.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#foot=
note-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !=
important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;=
">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> The first point is that, if the US government=C2=A0<em>does=C2=A0</em>=
default, that will probably cause the prices of Treasury bonds to go=C2=A0<=
em>up</em>, since a government debt default is a crisis and crises cause a =
flight to safety and the safest assets are, still, Treasuries:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is certainly not our modal vi=
ew, but in the unlikely event of a technical default, we think Treasury yie=
lds would decline and the curve would steepen. This seems unusual in the co=
ntext of a default, but Treasuries have rallied into the latter stages of o=
ther serious debt ceiling debates in 2011 and 2013.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">From first principles, if a US debt default do=
es not reduce the=C2=A0<em>value=C2=A0</em>of Treasuries, then Treasuries s=
hould remain pretty useful for plumbing and collateral purposes. Of course =
very little about financial plumbing is derived directly from first princip=
les, and if your computer has a switch that is like =E2=80=9CIF=C2=A0bond i=
s defaulted THEN don=E2=80=99t accept it as collateral,=E2=80=9D then there=
 are problems. But people have had years of debt-ceiling warnings to adjust=
 their switches and one hopes they have things kind of right:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Treasury can, in principle, delay coupon or pr=
incipal payment dates. If Treasury announces its intention to postpone a pa=
yment date in advance (the day before the payment is due), the security wil=
l remain in Fedwire, and would therefore still be transferable. =E2=80=A6</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If Treasury fails to notify investors of its i=
ntent to delay a principal payment due the following day by approximately 1=
0:00 PM, the security in question will drop out of Fedwire, and such defaul=
ted security will not be transferable. If (only) a coupon payment is missed=
, however, the underlying security is still in the system and remains trans=
ferable. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The status of Treasury collateral depends on t=
he timing of Treasury=E2=80=99s notification of any delays in payments. If =
done in the timeframe discussed earlier, the security remains in Fedwire an=
d is still transferable. As a result, it could in principal be used as coll=
ateral for repo and derivatives transactions, although possibly with higher=
 haircuts.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If notification deadlines are not met, particu=
larly for principal payments, that particular security is dropped out of th=
e system and is no longer transferable, and as a result, cannot be used as =
collateral. It is possible that an OTC market may develop for securities th=
at drop out of the system, but the likelihood of such an outcome is unclear=
 at the present time.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Since Treasury securities do not have cross-de=
fault provisions, other Treasury securities that have not had a delayed/mis=
sed payment will remain transferable on Fedwire and can therefore continue =
to be used as collateral. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Under the US non-cleared margin requirements (=
NCMR) finalized by CFTC and prudential regulators, Treasury securities are =
considered eligible collateral even in the case of a missed payment. Howeve=
r, this is not the case under the UK and EU NCMR regimes. Thus, for any tra=
nsactions facing counterparties in those regions, defaulted Treasury securi=
ties would be assigned zero collateral value, requiring the swap counterpar=
ty to substitute or post additional collateral. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We believe the Federal Reserve will accept def=
aulted Treasuries as collateral at the discount window.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so on. Money market funds, for instance, h=
old about $1 trillion of short-term Treasuries; =E2=80=9Cultimately,=E2=80=
=9D say JPMorgan, =E2=80=9Cwe believe these funds would not be forced to li=
quidate Treasury securities in a technical default.=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"foo=
tnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !importa=
nt; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I want to make a couple of points here:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">I assume that they are basically corr=
ect not to be <em>too=C2=A0</em>worried about the plumbing. We have been ha=
ving debt-ceiling crises every few years for ages now, and surely everyone =
has war-gamed this out over and over again. Financial markets are not full =
of idiots, and it would be annoying if this=C2=A0extremely predictable and =
predicted event=C2=A0brings down the global financial system through some t=
echnicality.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">That said, I as=
sume that with, like, 85% confidence. There is a lot of=C2=A0<em>stuff=C2=
=A0</em>out there. Surely the biggest global banks and asset managers have =
gamed out how they will keep markets going in the event of a US default, bu=
t is there some smaller firm whose computers will say =E2=80=9CTreasury pri=
ce =3D $0=E2=80=9D and cause chaos? Maybe!</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-botto=
m: 5px;">If <em>you=C2=A0</em>work in some corner of financial plumbing tha=
t you think=C2=A0<em>won=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>work in the event of a default=
, please do let me know! Send me an email. Also, though, fix it? You still =
have a little bit of time, and you=E2=80=99ve had plenty of warning.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Wouldn=E2=80=99t it be so tiresome to =
work in financial plumbing at some big bank and have to go to all the meeti=
ngs about this stuff? To have to build all the systems to deal with a US go=
vernment default, just because the US government can never get its act toge=
ther to get rid of the debt ceiling,=C2=A0and because debt-ceiling negotiat=
ions always have to go to the last second? Like imagine pulling the all-nig=
hters at JPMorgan to prepare for this, scrambling to save the US government=
 from the consequences of its own incompetence and malice, and meanwhile th=
e Securities and Exchange Commission is fining because <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31573672.259422/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb2=
1iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDktMjgvdGhlLWRlbGktd2FzLWFsbGVnZ=
WRseS1hLWZyYXVkP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MjMyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwm=
dXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDUyMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXl=
zdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8aed3ff9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  sometimes you text you=
r colleagues about work</a>. Just pay your debts, come on.</li>
</ol>
