<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Loosely speaking,=C2=A0Silicon Valley Bank con=
sisted of:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Some bank deposits;</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Some long-term US government bonds that lost a lot=
 of value as interest rates went up; and</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom:=
 5px;">Strong customer relationships with top tech startups and venture cap=
ital firms.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you acquired all of SVB =E2=80=94=C2=A0for =
instance by buying it from the US Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. after it =
failed and was seized =E2=80=94=C2=A0then you would get all of those things=
. The liabilities (Thing 1) seem to have been bigger than the assets (Thing=
 2), making the net value of SVB=E2=80=99s <em>balance sheet=C2=A0</em>nega=
tive. Which is awkward: You=C2=A0<em>could=C2=A0</em>pay the FDIC a negativ=
e amount of money for SVB, and in fact the buyer =E2=80=94=C2=A0First Citiz=
ens Bank &amp; Trust Co. =E2=80=94<em>=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/31573672.259422/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvb=
S9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMTAvY29tcGFuaWVzLWFyZS1hbGxvd2VkLXRvLWRv=
LWJhZC1tZXJnZXJzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MjMyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWw=
mdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDUyMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZX=
lzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB94c50f48" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">did</a></em><a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31573672.259422/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMTAvY29tcGFuaWVzLWFy=
ZS1hbGxvd2VkLXRvLWRvLWJhZC1tZXJnZXJzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MjMyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV=
0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDUyMyZ1dG=
1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC94c50f48" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> pa=
y a negative amount of money</a>=C2=A0(for much but not all of SVB), but th=
e FDIC was not really looking for a negative amount of money and it renders=
 the negotiations unpleasant.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In general, Thing 3 has a positive but uncerta=
in value. If some other bank had bought SVB in, like, January, it might hav=
e paid a positive amount of money for the whole bank: Sure the assets were =
worth less than the liabilities, but the=C2=A0<em>business=C2=A0</em>was va=
luable, not just the balance sheet. If you acquire a beloved bank with stro=
ng customer relationships, you can make money on that, even if its current =
pile of assets happens to be worth less than what it owes depositors.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But=C2=A0once you are negotiating with the FDI=
C to buy SVB out of receivership you might worry that those customer relati=
onships have decayed a bit.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also you can just buy them directly, for cheap=
, without messing around with the balance sheet? Bloomberg=E2=80=99s <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31573672.259422/aHR0cHM6=
Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMjIvZmlyc3QtY2l0aXp=
lbnMtc3Vlcy1oc2JjLWZvci1wb2FjaGluZy1kb3plbnMtb2Ytc3ZiLXN0YWZmP2NtcGlkPUJCRD=
A1MjMyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJ=
nV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDUyMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cB7cb6d2c0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">Joel Rosenblatt reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">First Citizens Bank &amp; Trust Co. sued HSBC =
Holdings Plc for allegedly raiding dozens of employees from Silicon Valley =
Bank in a scheme dubbed =E2=80=9CProject Colony=E2=80=9D as First Citizens =
was taking over the failed California lender.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Two weeks after First Citizens acquired SVB on=
 March 27, HSBC poached 42 bankers on Easter Sunday and brazenly took and m=
isused SVB=E2=80=99s confidential, proprietary and trade secret information=
, according to a complaint filed Monday in federal court in northern Califo=
rnia.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">David Sabow, who worked in a health-care and t=
echnology banking practice at SVB before jumping to HSBC, is identified in =
the complaint as =E2=80=9Cthe chief architect of this scheme,=E2=80=9D whic=
h aimed to plunder what was thought to be the =E2=80=9Ccore of SVB=E2=80=99=
s profitability engine,=E2=80=9D according to the complaint. Sabow helped t=
o identify six core US leaders to hire, along with 35 additional SVB profes=
sionals, according to the complaint.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yes right if there=E2=80=99s an insolvent bank=
 you want to acquire its=C2=A0<em>profitability engine=C2=A0</em>and leave =
its=C2=A0<em>balance sheet=C2=A0</em>behind.</p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Patent sub-trolls</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you invent a thing and patent it, and then =
somebody else makes a similar thing that infringes on your patent, you can =
sue them. For various reasons, this may be inconvenient for you, as an inve=
ntor: You may not have money to pay for lawyers, or you might be too busy i=
nventing and making stuff to sue, etc.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But you can sell your patents to somebody else=
. You can, for instance, sell your patent to somebody who is not in the bus=
iness of inventing and making things, but who is in the business of acquiri=
ng patents and=C2=A0suing people who make things that allegedly infringe on=
 the patents. This is a business that benefits from scale; the people in th=
is business =E2=80=94=C2=A0sometimes called =E2=80=9Cnon-practicing entitie=
s,=E2=80=9D or more=C2=A0pejoratively =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31573672.259422/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3=
JnL3dpa2kvUGF0ZW50X3Ryb2xs/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4d83c772" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">paten=
t trolls</a>=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0will want to acquire lots of patents a=
nd sue a lot to maximize their returns.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The downside of scale in litigation is that, i=
f you are constantly suing everyone in the world for infringing on your por=
tfolio of patents, people are going to start rolling their eyes when they s=
ee your lawsuits. =E2=80=9CThese guys again,=E2=80=9D they will say. =E2=80=
=9CPatent trolls,=E2=80=9D they will say.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But you can sell your patents to somebody else=
. You can, for instance, find some guy, and give him one of your patents, a=
nd then pay for him to sue people who make things that allegedly infringe o=
n the patents, and sign an agreement with him where he=E2=80=99ll give you =
most of the money if he wins and just keep a little tip for himself for let=
ting you use his name. And then when=C2=A0<em>he=C2=A0</em>sues,=C2=A0<em>h=
e=C2=A0</em>doesn=E2=80=99t have a long history of patent litigation, and m=
aybe people won=E2=80=99t roll their eyes at him.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or maybe they will. The <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31573672.259422/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNv=
bS9hcnRpY2xlcy9kZWxhd2FyZS1qdWRnZS10YXJnZXRzLXNlY3JldC1mdW5kaW5nLW9mLWxhd3N=
1aXRzLWIwZmU2MDhiP21vZD1pdHBfd3NqJnJ1PXlhaG9v/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB62db=
04ad" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;">Wall Street Journal reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A federal judge in Delaware is on a campaign t=
o eliminate hidden funding of intellectual-property lawsuits against compan=
ies, a crackdown that is roiling the patent-law industry.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">U.S. Chief District Judge Colm Connolly in Wil=
mington, whose court is one of the busiest venues for patent litigation, is=
sued an order a year ago requiring litigants in his court to disclose detai=
ls of any financial arrangements in which third parties are funding their l=
awsuits.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Lawyers defending companies against infringeme=
nt claims have cheered him on, crediting the judge with exposing tactics th=
at have shielded filers of frivolous lawsuits from scrutiny and liability. =
Attorneys representing plaintiffs in the judge=E2=80=99s crosshairs have ac=
cused Connolly of unjustly prying into their clients=E2=80=99 finances and =
privileged communications. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The largest fallout from Connolly=E2=80=99s ca=
mpaign involves IP Edge, a Houston-based company that makes money acquiring=
 vast bundles of patents and litigating them in court. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Last summer he summoned several Texas resident=
s identified as sole owners of plaintiff companies to testify at evidentiar=
y hearings he convened in November.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The witnesses, a paralegal from Fort Worth, a =
software salesman from Houston and a food-truck owner from Waco, testified =
that they came to own the rights to patents through a consulting firm calle=
d Mavexar that approached them.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Public records show that Mavexar=E2=80=99s thr=
ee principal members are the same patent attorneys that founded IP Edge. A =
lawyer for IP Edge declined to comment.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The witnesses all testified that Mavexar creat=
ed limited liability companies=E2=80=94naming them as managing members=E2=
=80=94and transferred patent rights to the companies. Mavexar retained atto=
rneys for the LLCs, handled communications with the lawyers and controlled =
decisions about wielding the patents in litigation, they said. The witnesse=
s said they didn=E2=80=99t pay anything for the rights to the patents but M=
avexar was entitled to 90%-95% of any litigation and settlement proceeds.=
=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Why does no one ever approach=C2=A0<em>me=C2=
=A0</em>out of the blue to give=C2=A0me 10% of some patent litigation? I me=
an, to be fair, I wouldn=E2=80=99t believe them, and I=E2=80=99d probably w=
rite about it. Still.=C2=A0</p>
