XBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6ed2a989" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked =
about the CDS situation</a> a few weeks ago: If the government defaults, th=
at should trigger credit default swaps, and the payout on CDS will depend o=
n essentially the trading price of the Treasury with the lowest dollar pric=
e. Treasuries might rally if the government defaults, but since some long-d=
ated Treasuries were issued at near-zero interest rates, they are trading w=
ay below par, and there would be real money in the CDS payout.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-3" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[3] Money market funds also invest in reverse =
repo, where they lend cash and get back longer-dated Treasuries as collater=
al: =E2=80=9CAlthough a delayed coupon payment is less consequential from a=
 risk perspective than a delayed principal payment, it is possible that MMF=
 and other repo participants will begin excluding these from the lists of e=
ligible collateral they are willing to accept, resulting in higher financin=
g costs for these issues. Similarly, dealers may demand higher haircuts on =
bonds with coupons in June, which may also bias yields higher on these secu=
rities. But since the risk here is a delayed coupon and not the principal, =
the haircut increases may not be severe.=E2=80=9D</p>
</div>
